{"review":"This paper presents a unified optimization-based framework that casts various graph convolutional network (GCN) variants as instances of a Laplacian-regularized least-squares problem in the graph Fourier domain, and proposes a novel feature-variance regularizer to mitigate oversmoothing. Strengths: 1. The framework offers a clear, unifying mathematical interpretation of vanilla GCN, attention-based GCNs, and topology-based methods such as PPNP and MixHop through carefully chosen regularizers. 2. The proposed feature-variance regularizer is well motivated and addresses oversmoothing by explicitly penalizing collapse of feature dimensions. 3. Empirical results on Cora, Citeseer, Pubmed, and PPI show consistent, modest gains (0.5–1.0% accuracy) over strong baselines, including comparison to DropEdge and PairNorm.

Weaknesses: 1. Novelty is limited: related work in graph signal processing (e.g., Hoang & Maehara 2019; Zhao & Akoglu 2019) already interprets GCNs as low-pass filters, and the unified formulation mainly assembles prior observations. 2. The reliance on first-order Taylor approximations weakens the theoretical claims, but no error bounds are provided. 3. Experiments focus on small citation graphs; scaling behavior and runtime overhead of the Kronecker-based regularizer (even with iterative approximation) are not analyzed. 4. Some key baselines (e.g., DropEdge, PPNP variants) are only briefly touched; an ablation on approximation order and sensitivity to hyperparameters is missing.

Actionable suggestions: 1. Provide theoretical guarantees or empirical analysis of approximation error introduced by the Taylor expansion. 2. Include runtime and memory cost comparisons on larger graphs. 3. Expand experiments to other domains (e.g., heterophilous graphs or link prediction). 4. Clarify novelty relative to existing graph signal processing interpretations and position this work accordingly. 5. Release code and hyperparameter settings for reproducibility.","rating":"5: Marginally below acceptance threshold"}

{"review":"This paper addresses an important gap between the theory and practice of adaptive gradient methods by studying their convergence in the over-parameterized (interpolation) setting. Under smooth convex interpolation, the authors prove that constant-step AMSGrad achieves an O(1/T) rate and that AdaGrad similarly converges at this faster rate when interpolation is exact. They further show that when interpolation is only approximate, both methods still converge to a small neighborhood of the optimum, and AdaGrad remains robust to interpolation violation. To remove the need for tuning, the paper integrates stochastic line-search (SLS) and Polyak step-sizes (SPS) into AdaGrad and AMSGrad, proving that these variants adapt to local smoothness without prior knowledge of Lipschitz constants while retaining convergence guarantees. The empirical evaluation is extensive, spanning synthetic convex problems, RBF kernel classification, deep matrix factorization, and image classification on CIFAR and ImageNet variants. Across tasks, AdaGrad/AMSGrad with SLS consistently outperforms tuned SGD, Adam, and recent Adam variants, often improving both convergence speed and generalization.

Weaknesses include: (1) the theoretical analysis is limited to smooth convex objectives and does not extend to non-convex deep networks; (2) the worst-case constants in the convergence bounds are loose, leaving a gap to SGD rates; (3) the momentum analysis yields no theoretical benefit and imposes restrictive parameter ranges; (4) line-search overhead and hyperparameter sensitivity (e.g., choice of c) warrant further discussion. 

To strengthen the work, I suggest: (i) outlining a path toward non-convex convergence analysis under interpolation; (ii) tightening constants or providing data-dependent bounds; (iii) adding an ablation on line-search cost vs. gains; and (iv) exploring alternative momentum formulations that yield provable benefits.","rating":"8: Top 50% of accepted papers, clear accept"}

{"review":"This paper proposes VISTA-Net, a unified structured attention mechanism for dense pixel-wise prediction that jointly models spatial and channel dependencies as a low-rank tensor within a CRF-inspired variational framework. Strengths: 1. The integration of structured attention as a sum of rank-1 tensors is clearly motivated and elegantly cast into a variational inference procedure implemented via standard neural network operations. 2. Extensive experiments on six benchmarks across tasks (segmentation, depth, normals) demonstrate consistent gains over strong baselines (DANet, SANet, MS-CRF, AG-CRF) and set new state-of-the-art results. 3. The ablation study shows the value of both the structured tensor formulation and the probabilistic treatment. 4. The paper is generally well written with detailed derivations and clear diagrams.

Weaknesses: 1. Novelty is limited: structured attention and attention-gated CRFs have been explored in prior work; the main contribution is combining them with low-rank tensor factorization. 2. The choice of tensor rank T lacks theoretical justification and only a single ablation on one dataset is presented; it is unclear how to select T in practice. 3. Computational cost is high (under 1 FPS on Pascal-Context) and memory overhead of the CRF updates is not analyzed. 4. Some implementation details are missing: the initialization and convergence behavior of the variational updates, and sensitivity to hyperparameters (e.g., weighting factors b) are not reported.

Actionable suggestions: 1. Provide guidance on choosing T and include rank-sensitivity on additional tasks. 2. Report GPU memory usage and run-time on all benchmarks, and compare to transformer-style self-attention in efficiency. 3. Clarify initialization of latent variables, update scheduling, and convergence criteria. 4. Discuss limitations when scaling to higher resolution or more modalities.","rating":"6: Marginally above acceptance threshold"}
